Submitted brands should usually be corporate, master, or primary consumer brands when the cited leader has company-wide responsibility. Portfolio brands, product lines, and sub-brands count only when the page ties the person to that exact submitted brand.

Each URL should be a substantive public source about the brand initiative: for example, an article, interview, campaign case study, awards or creative database entry, brand newsroom feature, filing, or executive commentary. Static leadership bios, LinkedIn or Wikipedia-style profiles, company homepages, thin rankings/lists, and bare appointment notices do not count by themselves.

Requirements:
- The page should communicate that it is a substantive public source about a concrete brand initiative, not merely a page that names the person and title.
- The page must identify the exact submitted brand and named person, and tie the person to the selected leadership lane through a title, role, credit, quoted responsibility, or comparable context.
- The page must describe a concrete brand initiative in {= initiative_window =} and tie the person to leading, owning, creating, explaining, being credited for, or being accountable for that initiative.
